      h1 Takayama 
      h2 Day 5 - Friday – Takayama
      p We checked out of our hotel in Matsumoto and made the long journey to Takayama. We took the Limited Express to Nagoya and then the Limited Express to Takayama. The trip took about 5 hours. The train from Nagoya to Takayama was a slow train through the mountains, past ski resorts and through very snowy areas. In fact Takayama gets a lot of snow every year due to its proximity to the Sea of Japan and the "lake" effect snow.
      p 
       ' We arrived in the late afternoon to Takayama and walked to our hotel, 
       a href="http://www.rickshawinn.com/e/" target="_blank" title="Rickshaw Inn" Rickshaw Inn
       ' . I had high hopes for this place based on 
       a href="http://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g298113-d320170-Reviews-Rickshaw_Inn-Takayama_Gifu_Prefecture_Chubu.html" target="_blank" title="Rickshaw Inn TripAdvisor reviews" TripAdvisor reviews
       ' , but it wasn't too fantastic. First off, there was no central heating, and our room was unbelievably cold. They turned on the heater when we arrived but it took a long time to heat up. We had a Japanese style room, and sleeping on the floor was fine, but the accommodations were very basic. 
      p 
       ' For the first evening, we found a hole-in-the-wall restaurant called 
       a href="http://www.happycow.net/reviews.php?id=29092" target="_blank" title="Heianraku Restaurant" Heianraku
       ' . They had things like stir-fried noodles, and it was fantastic. I had chicken in mine, but there were vegetarian options. The owner spoke great English and was happy to converse with us. We also shared a big bottle of beer. It was a great experience.
      h2 Day 6 — Saturday – Takayama
      p We headed out early to hit the morning market. It was a cold and rainy day, and there were only a couple of stalls there so it wasn't really worth going. 
      p Afterwards, we walked around the beautiful old district. This is one of the most well preserved Edo Period places. It really feels like Japan there. 
